      "role": "user",
      "content": "the problem is we're on a very constrained micro-controller architecture so i can't really run valgrind or anything that heavy. it's basically just raw pointers and some manual memory management. since it's so slow and subtle, it feels like the leak is hiding in some corner of the logic that only hits under specific conditions. any ideas on how to narrow down the search area without a full debugger?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, dealing with a constrained micro-controller architecture means we need to be more resourceful. Here's a more tailored approach to find your memory leak:\n\n1. **Custom Memory Tracking:**\n   - Implement a custom memory tracking system. Create a simple counter for allocations and deallocations, perhaps using global variables. Make sure to include this counter in the beginning and end of each memory allocation and deallocation function.\n\n2. **Instrumentation:**\n   - Instrument critical sections of your code, especially those that are called frequently or under specific conditions you suspect might trigger the leak. Add log statements to record the timestamps and memory usage before and after these sections.\n\n3. **Conditional Breakpoints:**\n   - Since you can't run a heavy profiler, use conditional compilation to create breakpoints. Compile your code with additional debug code that only compiles under certain conditions, such as a specific memory usage threshold or after a certain number of allocations.\n\n4. **Memory Pooling:**\n   - Consider implementing a memory pooling technique to manage allocations more predictably. This can help you track down leaks by giving you a more controlled environment to measure memory usage.\n\n5. **Static Analysis:**\n   - Use static analysis tools that are lightweight and suitable for embedded environments.",
